Content:
I came across this while considering the subset sum problem in relation to another problem. Define the ratio, $$R(n,k) = \frac{\binom n k}{n^{k-1}}$$ and the integer sequence with initial $k=1$ , $$s_k = k!+\frac{k(k-1)}{2} = 1, 3, 9, 30, 130, 735,\dots$$ Q: How do we show that, $$\begin{aligned}
R\big(n,\,k\big)\; &< 1,\quad\text{if}\;n < s_k\\
R\big(n,\,k\big)\; &\geq 1,\quad\text{if}\;n \geq s_k
\end{aligned}$$ Examples. Let $k=5\,$ so $s_5 = 130$ , then, $$\begin{aligned}
R\big(129,\,5\big)\; &=\frac{\binom{129}{5}}{129^4} = 0.9939\dots\\[5pt]
R\big(130,\,5\big)\; &=\frac{\binom{130}{5}}{130^4} = 1.0022\dots
\end{aligned}$$ Let $k=6\,$ so $s_6 = 735$ , then, $$\begin{aligned}
R\big(734,\,6\big)\; &=\frac{\binom{734}{6}}{734^5} = 0.99877\dots\\[5pt]
R\big(735,\,6\big)\; &=\frac{\binom{735}{6}}{735^5} = 1.00016\dots
\end{aligned}$$ and so on. Update. Note that: $$t_k = \frac{2\,s_k}{k} = 2, 3, 6, 15, 52, 245,\dots$$ is A370888 (added 2024), or the 5-card trick, with maximum deck size $52$ .
